    {
      "id": "db627413_c4c26fb1",
      "file_path": "cps-path-parser/src/main/java/org/onap/cps/cpspath/parser/CpsPathBuilder.java",
      "patchset_number": 7,
      "line": 213,
      "message": "If a string wrapped in a single quote why does it makes sense to perform a String.replace on a sequence which is possibly not present in the string? (Especially if you remove the 1st and last characters?)\n\nFor example \" 'test' \" should become \"test\" here and replacing '' with ' would have no effect here.\n\nOr am I not seeing something?",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 8155,
        "name": "Levente Csanyi",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "levente.csanyi@est.tech",
        "username": "leventecsanyi"
      },
      "updated": "2023-07-20 12:36:25.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": null,
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "f3882a0f_6921fb22",
      "file_path": "cps-path-parser/src/main/java/org/onap/cps/cpspath/parser/CpsPathBuilder.java",
      "patchset_number": 7,
      "line": 213,
      "message": "So you can use double-quotes inside quotes and reverse like this:\n\n    \"I'm escaped\"  -> I'm escaped\n    'I\"m escaped'  -> I\"m escaped\n\nBut if you want to use the SAME type of quotes, you double them:\n\n    'I''m escaped' -> I'm escaped\n    \"I\"\"m escaped\" -> I\"m escaped\n\nThis is all in the context of CpsPaths, so it would be really something like this:\n    \n    //books[@title='I''m escaped']\n\nto get a book called \"I'm escaped\".\n    \nThe reason we replace is so that the DataNode.dataLeaves will contain \"I'm escaped\" not \"I''m escaped\", otherwise it would look for wrong leaf value.\nI hope this makes sense.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 6742,
        "name": "Daniel Hanrahan",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "daniel.hanrahan@est.tech",
        "username": "danielhanrahan"
      },
      "updated": "2023-07-20 12:49:28.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "db627413_c4c26fb1",
      "unresolved": true
    },
